In <3usupo$7g6@steel.interlog.com>, "S.Lee" <sllee@interlog.com> writes:
>If you are a good businessman, what would you do? Write a program that
>have a hugh market for it or write a program that is not supported by the
>general public?  I think the answer speaks for itself!

Sometimes having a large share of a small market is better than having a
tiny share of a huge market.

You can only get a large share of a given platform's users if you release an
application that most of them need, such as a word processor.  Now, would a
*good* businessman put his efforts behind a word processor for Windows
hoping to unseat Word and WordPerfect?  No.

Unless you can come up with the next innovative application that EVERYONE
needs, you have to find a more "niche" product in a market where you can get
some penetration.

Seeing as how all the Windows advocates keep claiming that "there are no
OS/2 apps" for it's nearly 8 million users, it seems that there's quite a
market there.

